  "abstract": "The philosophy and approach of plant disease management have k e n greatly\r\n.influenced by the evolution of an Integrated Pest Management concept, developed\r\noriginally as an integrated control approach for insects(57). This concept has\r\ndeveloped into a holistic, multidisciplinary management system that integrates control\r\nmethods, on the basis of ecological and cconomic principles, for pests of all classes\r\nthat coexist in an agroecosystem(l3). Disease management is an integral part of the\r\ncrop management system and it implies that diseases are inherent components of thc\r\nagroecosystem that must be dealt with on a continuous knowledgeable basis.\r\nManagement is based on the principle of maintain~ng( he damage or crop loss below\r\nan cconomic injury level. Plant disease epidemics result from the conjunction of host,\r\npathogen, weather and time(73) and variations in any of these factors greatly\r\ninfluence the course of an epidemic.",
